{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491661"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1013"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1013"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.15,0.03,0.02,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1013"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92861"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1013"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1013"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76226"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9055"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2516"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31216"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43829"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92861"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intermittent and painless passage of blood per rectum. This typically occurs when he is constipated. He reports bouts of constipation alternating with normal bowel movements. He has noticed small amounts of blood streaked on the surface of the faeces, sometimes with mucus. He has never had these symptoms before. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Digital rectal examination is unremarkable. Proctoscopy shows some fleshy haemorrhoids. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin = 107 g/L (128-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCV = 68 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWBC = 9.1 \u00a0x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets = 220 \u00a0x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High fibre diet","Rubber band ligation","Injection sclerotherapy","CT abdomen and pelvis","Colonoscopy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with rectal bleeding and has evidence of iron deficiency anaemia (low haemoglobin and low MCV). Although \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is invasive, it is the most appropriate next step to exclude colorectal malignancy, which can present with similar symptoms. While haemorrhoids are visible on proctoscopy and could explain the bleeding, the presence of red flags (change in bowel habit and iron deficiency anaemia) necessitates a complete examination of the colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh fibre diet\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate management for haemorrhoids and constipation, but it would not address the need to exclude more serious pathology. Given the red flags present, treating only the haemorrhoids without investigating further would be inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERubber band ligation\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective treatment for symptomatic internal haemorrhoids. However, this would be premature before excluding other causes of bleeding, particularly given the presence of iron deficiency anaemia which suggests chronic blood loss that may not be fully explained by the haemorrhoids seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInjection sclerotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is another treatment option for haemorrhoids, but like rubber band ligation, it would be inappropriate to proceed with this before excluding more serious pathology such as colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful for staging if colorectal cancer is found, but it is not the first-line investigation for suspected colorectal cancer. Colonoscopy offers direct visualisation of the mucosa and the ability to take biopsies, making it superior for initial diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while colorectal cancer has traditionally been considered a disease of older adults, there has been an increasing incidence in younger patients. Therefore, age alone should not be used to exclude the possibility of colorectal cancer, especially in the presence of red flags such as change in bowel habit and iron deficiency anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colorectal malignancy must be considered in all patients with rectal bleeding, regardless of age, especially when accompanied by iron deficiency anaemia.","Haemorrhoids should never be assumed to be the sole cause of rectal bleeding until more serious pathology has been excluded.","Red flags for colorectal cancer include change in bowel habit, iron deficiency anaemia, weight loss, and family history of colorectal cancer."],"references":["Mott T, Latimer K, Edwards C. Hemorrhoids: Diagnosis and Treatment Options. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Feb 1;97(3):172-179. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29431977/","Bleday R, Breen E. Hemorrhoids: Clinical manifestations and diagnosis. In: UptoDate. Waltham (MA); 2020. [updated 2021 Mar; cited 2021 Apr 26]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/hemorrhoids-clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76226"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1013"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76226"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T18:55:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-19T18:56:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1013"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92861"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms